const sops = [
  { title: "Sterile Agar Preparation", category: "Lab Technique", difficulty_level: "Beginner", estimated_time: "2-3 hours", content: "## Sterile Agar Preparation\n\n### Purpose\nPrepare nutrient agar plates for mushroom culture isolation, transfers, and long-term storage.\n\n### Materials Needed\n- Light malt extract (20g/L)\n- Agar powder (20g/L)\n- Distilled water (1 liter)\n- Petri dishes (sterile, 100mm)\n- Pressure cooker (15 PSI capable)\n- Media bottle or Erlenmeyer flask\n- Aluminum foil\n- Parafilm or micropore tape\n\n### Procedure\n1. **Measure ingredients**: Combine 20g light malt extract + 20g agar powder per 1L distilled water in a media bottle\n2. **Mix thoroughly**: Swirl to combine — agar won't fully dissolve until heated\n3. **Cap loosely**: Cover with foil or loosen media bottle cap for steam venting\n4. **Sterilize**: Pressure cook at 15 PSI for 20 minutes. Start timing when gauge reaches 15 PSI\n5. **Cool to pouring temp**: Let media cool to ~120-130°F (warm but holdable)\n6. **Pour plates**: Working in front of flow hood or in SAB, pour ~20mL per plate. Fill to about 1/3 depth\n7. **Let solidify**: Leave plates undisturbed for 30-60 minutes with lids slightly cracked\n8. **Seal and store**: Wrap plate edges with parafilm. Store inverted (lid down) at room temperature\n\n### Quality Checks\n- Plates should be crystal clear with no cloudiness\n- No condensation pooling on agar surface after 24 hours\n- No contamination growth after 3 days at room temperature\n\n### Tips\n- Adding 1g nutritional yeast per liter enhances growth for many species\n- Work in front of a flow hood or inside a still air box for best results\n- Pour plates quickly once at correct temperature — agar sets fast\n- Label plates with date, media type, and any additives", equipment_needed: ["Pressure cooker", "Flow hood or SAB", "Petri dishes", "Scale", "Media bottle"], safety_warnings: ["Hot media causes severe burns", "Never force-cool pressure cooker", "Work in sterile environment"], success_rate: 95.0, is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Grain Spawn Preparation (Rye Berries)", category: "Spawn Production", difficulty_level: "Beginner", estimated_time: "4-6 hours (plus overnight soak)", content: "## Grain Spawn Preparation — Rye Berries\n\n### Purpose\nPrepare sterilized grain spawn for inoculation with liquid culture or agar wedge.\n\n### Materials Needed\n- Whole rye berries (organic preferred)\n- Large pot for simmering\n- Strainer/colander\n- Gypsum (calcium sulfate) — 1 tbsp per quart jar\n- Quart mason jars with modified lids (injection port + filter patch)\n- Pressure cooker (15 PSI)\n- Aluminum foil\n\n### Procedure\n1. **Rinse grain**: Rinse rye berries under running water to remove dust and debris\n2. **Soak**: Cover with water + 2 inches. Soak 12-24 hours (overnight)\n3. **Simmer**: Bring to gentle simmer for 15-20 minutes. Grains should be hydrated but NOT splitting\n4. **Drain and dry**: Drain in colander. Spread on clean towels or mesh screen for 30-60 minutes. Surface moisture is the enemy — grains should feel dry to touch\n5. **Add gypsum**: Toss grains with gypsum (1 tbsp per quart). Prevents clumping\n6. **Load jars**: Fill quart jars to 3/4 full. Don't pack tight — grains need room to shake\n7. **Seal**: Apply modified lids, cover with foil\n8. **Sterilize**: Pressure cook at 15 PSI for 90-120 minutes\n9. **Cool**: Let jars cool 8-12 hours in PC. Do not open until fully cool\n\n### Quality Checks\n- No burst or mushy grains\n- Grains should be individual, not clumping\n- No excess moisture pooling at jar bottom\n- Foil should show condensation (indicates proper steam)\n\n### Tips\n- The #1 cause of grain spawn contamination is too much moisture\n- Shake jars after inoculation and again at 30% colonization\n- Store prepared (uninoculated) jars for up to 2 weeks before use\n- If grains burst, simmer time was too long", equipment_needed: ["Pressure cooker", "Mason jars with modified lids", "Large pot", "Strainer", "Scale"], safety_warnings: ["Pressure cooker safety protocols", "Hot steam burns", "Never open PC under pressure"], success_rate: 90.0, is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Monotub Fruiting Chamber Build", category: "Fruiting", difficulty_level: "Beginner", estimated_time: "1-2 hours", content: "## Monotub Fruiting Chamber Build\n\n### Purpose\nBuild a simple, effective automated fruiting chamber for bulk substrate cultivation.\n\n### Materials Needed\n- 66-quart clear storage tote with lid\n- 2-inch hole saw or soldering iron\n- Polyfill stuffing\n- Micropore tape\n- Drill or soldering iron\n- Marker\n\n### Procedure\n1. **Mark holes**: On each long side, mark 2 holes at ~4 inches from bottom (FAE). On each short side, mark 1 hole at ~4 inches from bottom\n2. **Drill holes**: Use 2-inch hole saw to cut all 6 holes\n3. **Stuff with polyfill**: Loosely stuff each hole with polyfill. Not too tight — air needs to passively flow\n4. **Lid holes**: Drill 2 holes in the lid for additional gas exchange (optional, species-dependent)\n5. **Test fit**: Place lid on tote, ensure snug fit with no gaps\n\n### Fruiting Protocol\n1. **Spawn to bulk**: Mix colonized grain spawn with pasteurized substrate at 1:2 to 1:4 ratio\n2. **Level and case**: Level substrate surface. Optionally add thin casing layer\n3. **Colonization**: Keep lid on with holes covered. Wait 7-14 days for full colonization\n4. **Introduce fruiting**: Uncover holes (or stuff loosely with polyfill). Mist walls if needed. Maintain 85-95% humidity\n5. **Harvest**: Pick mushrooms when veil begins to tear or just before\n\n### Tips\n- Clear totes let you monitor colonization without opening\n- Polyfill density controls air exchange rate\n- Mist the walls and lid, never directly on substrate\n- Fan with lid for 30 seconds 2x daily if polyfill exchange isn't enough", equipment_needed: ["66-qt storage tote", "2-inch hole saw", "Drill", "Polyfill", "Micropore tape"], safety_warnings: ["Wear eye protection when drilling", "Smooth hole edges to prevent cuts"], success_rate: 92.0, is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Substrate Pasteurization (Bucket Tek)", category: "Substrate Preparation", difficulty_level: "Beginner", estimated_time: "2-3 hours", content: "## Substrate Pasteurization — Bucket Tek\n\n### Purpose\nPasteurize straw or other bulk substrate using the bucket method — simple, reliable, no special equipment.\n\n### Materials Needed\n- 5-gallon bucket with lid\n- Chopped straw or hardwood fuel pellets\n- Boiling water\n- Thermometer\n- Strainer bag or pillowcase\n- Rubber gloves\n\n### Procedure\n1. **Prep substrate**: If using straw, chop to 2-3 inch lengths. If using hardwood fuel pellets, add to bucket — they'll expand with hot water\n2. **Pack bucket**: Fill bucket 3/4 full with dry substrate\n3. **Add boiling water**: Pour boiling water over substrate until fully submerged\n4. **Seal**: Place lid on bucket tightly\n5. **Wait**: Let sit for 60-90 minutes. Temperature should stay above 160°F for at least 60 minutes\n6. **Drain**: Carefully drain water (save for garden!). Let substrate drip until at field capacity\n7. **Field capacity test**: Squeeze a handful firmly — only a few drops should come out. If water streams, drain longer\n8. **Cool**: Spread on clean surface or leave in bucket until substrate reaches room temperature (~75°F)\n\n### Quality Checks\n- Substrate should smell fresh/earthy, not sour\n- Should pass field capacity test\n- No visible contamination after 3 days\n\n### Tips\n- This method works great for oyster mushrooms on straw\n- Hardwood fuel pellets are pre-pasteurized when dry — hot water soak is extra insurance\n- Never spawn to hot substrate — wait until below 80°F\n- Can add hydrated lime to water (1 tbsp per gallon) for extra pH-based pasteurization", equipment_needed: ["5-gallon bucket with lid", "Thermometer", "Kettle or large pot", "Strainer bag", "Rubber gloves"], safety_warnings: ["Boiling water burn risk", "Wear rubber gloves when handling hot substrate", "Let substrate cool completely before spawning"], success_rate: 93.0, is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Liquid Culture Preparation", category: "Lab Technique", difficulty_level: "Intermediate", estimated_time: "3-4 hours", content: "## Liquid Culture Preparation\n\n### Purpose\nCreate sterile liquid culture media for fast mycelium propagation and easy inoculation.\n\n### Materials Needed\n- Light malt extract or honey (4% solution: 40g per 1L)\n- Distilled water\n- Quart mason jars with modified lids (injection port + 0.2μm syringe filter)\n- Magnetic stir bar (optional)\n- Pressure cooker\n- Aquarium air pump + inline filter (for aerated LC)\n\n### Procedure\n1. **Mix media**: Dissolve 40g light malt extract (or 40g honey) in 600mL distilled water per quart jar\n2. **Add stir bar**: Drop a magnetic stir bar into each jar (optional but recommended)\n3. **Seal**: Apply modified lids with injection port and syringe filter\n4. **Cover**: Wrap lids with foil\n5. **Sterilize**: Pressure cook at 15 PSI for 20-30 minutes\n6. **Cool completely**: Wait 8-12 hours before inoculating\n7. **Inoculate**: Using sterile syringe, inject small piece of clean mycelium or spore solution through injection port\n8. **Incubate**: Keep at 75-78°F. Swirl jar daily or place on magnetic stir plate\n9. **Ready**: LC is ready when you see wispy mycelial mass floating in solution (typically 7-14 days)\n\n### Quality Checks\n- Media should be light amber and clear after sterilization\n- Mycelium should be white and wispy, not slimy\n- No bacterial contamination (cloudy solution = bacteria)\n- Test on agar plate before using for spawn\n\n### Tips\n- Always test LC on agar before committing grain to it\n- 4% concentration is optimal — too rich invites contamination\n- Honey works as well as malt extract and is easier to source\n- LC can be stored in fridge for 2-3 months", equipment_needed: ["Pressure cooker", "Mason jars with modified lids", "Syringe filters (0.2μm)", "Magnetic stir bar", "Scale"], safety_warnings: ["Pressure cooker safety", "Sterile technique required", "Test LC on agar before bulk use"], success_rate: 88.0, is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Still Air Box (SAB) Construction and Use", category: "Lab Technique", difficulty_level: "Beginner", estimated_time: "30 minutes to build", content: "## Still Air Box (SAB) Construction and Use\n\n### Purpose\nBuild a low-cost still air box for performing sterile transfers, agar work, and inoculation without a laminar flow hood.\n\n### Materials Needed\n- Large clear storage tote (50-66 quart)\n- Marker\n- Box cutter or hole saw\n- Micropore tape (optional for arm holes)\n- Isopropyl alcohol 70% spray bottle\n- Paper towels\n\n### Construction\n1. **Flip tote upside down**: The bottom of the tote becomes the top work surface (more stable)\n2. **Mark arm holes**: On one long side, mark two circles large enough for your forearms (4-5 inch diameter), spaced shoulder-width apart, about 4 inches from the bottom edge\n3. **Cut holes**: Use hole saw or carefully cut with box cutter. Smooth edges with sandpaper or tape\n4. **Optional**: Attach loose plastic sleeves with rubber bands for better seal\n\n### Usage Protocol\n1. **Pre-clean**: Wipe interior with 70% isopropyl alcohol\n2. **Load materials**: Place all needed items inside SAB (agar plates, scalpel, lighter, cultures)\n3. **Spray**: Mist interior with 70% ISO. The alcohol spray knocks down airborne particles\n4. **Wait 5 minutes**: Let air settle completely. Do NOT blow or fan inside the box\n5. **Insert arms slowly**: Avoid creating air currents\n6. **Work deliberately**: Slow, careful movements. Flame sterilize scalpel between transfers\n7. **Minimize openings**: Don't pull arms in and out repeatedly\n\n### Tips\n- A SAB is 95% as effective as a flow hood when used properly\n- The key is STILL air — no drafts, no movement\n- Work on an interior table away from HVAC vents\n- Spray 70% ISO liberally — it's your main contamination defense\n- Turn off ceiling fans and close doors before working", equipment_needed: ["Large clear storage tote", "Hole saw or box cutter", "70% isopropyl alcohol", "Spray bottle"], safety_warnings: ["Be careful cutting plastic", "70% ISO is flammable — no open flames while spraying", "Allow ISO to evaporate before using lighter"], success_rate: 90.0, is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Masters Mix Substrate Recipe", category: "Substrate Preparation", difficulty_level: "Intermediate", estimated_time: "4-5 hours", content: "## Masters Mix Substrate Recipe\n\n### Purpose\nPrepare the industry-standard supplemented sawdust substrate used by commercial mushroom farms worldwide.\n\n### Formula\nMasters Mix = 50% hardwood sawdust + 50% soy hull pellets (by dry weight), hydrated to 60% moisture content.\n\n### Materials Needed\n- Hardwood fuel pellets (oak, maple, or mixed hardwood)\n- Soy hull pellets\n- Water\n- Grow bags with filter patches (unicorn bags or similar)\n- Impulse sealer\n- Pressure cooker or autoclave\n- Scale\n\n### Procedure\n1. **Weigh dry ingredients**: 2.5 lbs hardwood pellets + 2.5 lbs soy hull pellets per bag (5 lb block)\n2. **Calculate water**: Add water to reach 60% moisture. For 5 lbs dry mix, add approximately 7.5 lbs (just under 1 gallon) water\n3. **Mix**: Combine pellets and water in a large tub. Let pellets absorb and break apart (15-30 min)\n4. **Break up clumps**: Mix thoroughly with hands or paddle. Should feel like wrung-out sponge\n5. **Fill bags**: Load 5 lbs of hydrated mix per bag. Fold top and seal with impulse sealer\n6. **Sterilize**: Autoclave or pressure cook at 15 PSI for 2.5 hours\n7. **Cool**: Let bags cool 12-24 hours before inoculation\n8. **Inoculate**: Open bag top in front of flow hood, add grain spawn (10-15% spawn rate), reseal\n\n### Tips\n- This is the go-to recipe for Lion's Mane, King Oyster, Pioppino, and most hardwood-loving species\n- Soy hulls provide the nitrogen supplement — don't skip them\n- Over-supplementation (>50% soy) dramatically increases contamination risk\n- Some growers add 1% gypsum for pH buffering\n- Masters Mix is NOT suitable for straw-loving species (oysters do fine on just straw)", equipment_needed: ["Autoclave or large pressure cooker", "Grow bags with filter patch", "Impulse sealer", "Scale", "Mixing tub"], safety_warnings: ["Pressure cooker safety — never exceed rated capacity", "Hot bags cause burns", "Work in sterile environment for inoculation"], success_rate: 88.0, is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Spore Print Collection", category: "Lab Technique", difficulty_level: "Beginner", estimated_time: "8-24 hours", content: "## Spore Print Collection\n\n### Purpose\nCollect a spore print from a mature mushroom for long-term genetic storage or spore syringe preparation.\n\n### Materials Needed\n- Fresh mature mushroom (veil just broken or gills fully exposed)\n- Aluminum foil (heavy duty)\n- Glass cup or bowl\n- Ziplock bag\n- Scalpel or sharp knife\n- 70% isopropyl alcohol\n\n### Procedure\n1. **Select specimen**: Choose a clean, healthy mushroom with fully opened cap. Gills should be exposed but not dried out\n2. **Prepare surface**: Cut a square of aluminum foil. Wipe with 70% ISO\n3. **Remove stem**: Cut stem flush with cap using sterile scalpel\n4. **Place cap**: Set cap gill-side down on foil\n5. **Cover**: Place clean glass over cap to prevent air currents and contamination\n6. **Wait**: Leave undisturbed for 8-24 hours at room temperature\n7. **Remove cap**: Carefully lift mushroom cap straight up. Spore print should be visible on foil\n8. **Fold and seal**: Fold foil over print, place in labeled ziplock bag\n9. **Store**: Keep in cool, dark, dry place. Spore prints can remain viable for years\n\n### Tips\n- Half foil, half white paper shows spore color beautifully\n- A single spore print can make dozens of spore syringes\n- Work in a clean area but full sterile technique isn't critical for printing\n- Some species drop spores faster than others\n- Thicker prints are better for long-term storage", equipment_needed: ["Aluminum foil", "Glass cup", "Scalpel", "70% isopropyl alcohol", "Ziplock bags"], safety_warnings: ["Only collect spore prints from positively identified species", "Some mushrooms are toxic — know your species", "Wash hands after handling"], success_rate: 95.0, is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Flow Hood Operation and Maintenance", category: "Lab Technique", difficulty_level: "Intermediate", estimated_time: "Ongoing", content: "## Flow Hood Operation and Maintenance\n\n### Purpose\nProperly operate and maintain a laminar flow hood for sterile mycology work.\n\n### Equipment\n- Laminar flow hood (horizontal or vertical)\n- HEPA filter (99.97% at 0.3 microns)\n- Pre-filter\n- 70% isopropyl alcohol\n- Spray bottle\n\n### Operating Procedure\n1. **Pre-run**: Turn on flow hood 15-30 minutes before working to purge air in workspace\n2. **Wipe down**: Clean all work surfaces inside hood with 70% ISO\n3. **Organize**: Place materials in hood — work 6+ inches from front edge\n4. **Work upstream**: Always work behind (downstream of) open containers. Never reach over open plates\n5. **Minimize disruption**: Keep arm movements slow and deliberate. Don't break the laminar flow plane unnecessarily\n6. **Close when done**: Turn off hood and cover front opening with plastic sheet when not in use\n\n### Maintenance Schedule\n- **Daily**: Wipe down work surface with 70% ISO\n- **Weekly**: Clean pre-filter, wipe exterior\n- **Monthly**: Inspect HEPA filter for damage, check blower performance\n- **Annually**: DOP/PAO test or particle count to verify HEPA integrity\n- **As needed**: Replace pre-filter (typically every 3-6 months)\n\n### Tips\n- A flow hood is the single best investment for serious mycology\n- Horizontal flow is generally preferred for mushroom work\n- Never spray ISO directly onto HEPA filter — it damages the media\n- If contamination rates increase suddenly, check HEPA seal and pre-filter\n- Work at least 6 inches inside the hood — the front edge is the dirty zone", equipment_needed: ["Laminar flow hood", "70% isopropyl alcohol", "Pre-filters", "Spray bottle"], safety_warnings: ["Electrical safety", "Don't spray alcohol on HEPA filter", "UV lights can damage eyes — never look directly at UV source"], success_rate: 98.0, is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Hardwood Log Inoculation (Shiitake)", category: "Outdoor Cultivation", difficulty_level: "Intermediate", estimated_time: "Full day (multiple logs)", content: "## Hardwood Log Inoculation for Shiitake\n\n### Purpose\nInoculate freshly cut hardwood logs with shiitake plug spawn for outdoor mushroom production.\n\n### Materials Needed\n- Fresh-cut hardwood logs (oak preferred), 3-6 inch diameter, 3-4 feet long\n- Shiitake plug spawn (or sawdust spawn)\n- 12mm drill bit (for plug spawn)\n- Drill\n- Cheese wax or beeswax\n- Small wax pot or old crockpot\n- Dauber or small paintbrush\n\n### Timing\n- Cut logs in late winter when trees are dormant (December-February)\n- Inoculate within 2-6 weeks of cutting\n- Bark must be intact — this is the mushroom's protective layer\n\n### Procedure\n1. **Drill holes**: Drill holes 6 inches apart in a diamond pattern. Rows spaced 2-3 inches apart around log circumference. Depth: just past bark into sapwood (~1.25 inches)\n2. **Insert spawn**: Tap plug spawn into each hole with rubber mallet. Plug should be flush with or slightly below bark surface\n3. **Seal with wax**: Melt cheese wax to ~300°F. Dab melted wax over each plug to seal. Also wax any cut ends or bark damage\n4. **Stack and incubate**: Stack logs in shaded area (forest canopy, north side of building). Crib-stack or lean against support\n5. **Wait**: Colonization takes 6-12 months depending on log diameter and species\n6. **Force fruit**: After colonization, soak logs in cold water for 24 hours to trigger fruiting\n7. **Harvest**: Shiitake appear 7-10 days after soaking. Harvest when caps are 70% open\n\n### Tips\n- Oak is king for shiitake — sugar maple works too\n- Never use softwood (pine, cedar) — wrong species\n- Logs can produce for 3-7 years depending on diameter\n- Soak every 8 weeks during growing season for continuous harvest\n- Keep logs off ground on pallets to prevent ground contamination", equipment_needed: ["Drill with 12mm bit", "Plug spawn", "Cheese wax", "Wax pot/crockpot", "Rubber mallet"], safety_warnings: ["Drill safety — wear eye protection", "Hot wax burns", "Proper lifting technique for heavy logs"], success_rate: 85.0, is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Spore Syringe Preparation", category: "Lab Technique", difficulty_level: "Intermediate", estimated_time: "1-2 hours", content: "## Spore Syringe Preparation\n\n### Purpose\nCreate a sterile spore syringe from a spore print for inoculating grain spawn or agar.\n\n### Materials Needed\n- Spore print on foil\n- Sterile water (distilled, pressure cooked)\n- Sterile 10-20cc syringes\n- Sterile 18ga needles\n- Shot glass or small sterile container\n- Still air box or flow hood\n- 70% isopropyl alcohol\n- Lighter/torch\n\n### Procedure\n1. **Prepare sterile water**: Pressure cook distilled water in sealed mason jar at 15 PSI for 30 minutes. Cool completely\n2. **Set up SAB/Flow Hood**: Clean workspace, spray with 70% ISO\n3. **Open spore print**: Carefully unfold foil with spore print inside workspace\n4. **Scrape spores**: Using sterile scalpel, gently scrape spores into shot glass\n5. **Add water**: Draw sterile water into syringe, squirt into shot glass with spores\n6. **Mix**: Draw solution in and out of syringe several times to distribute spores\n7. **Fill syringe**: Draw up full syringe of spore solution\n8. **Cap needle**: Replace needle cap or use silicone cap\n9. **Label**: Date, species, and source on label\n10. **Hydrate**: Let syringe sit at room temperature 24 hours before use (allows spores to hydrate)\n\n### Quality Checks\n- Hold syringe up to light — you should see tiny spore particles floating\n- Solution should not be cloudy (cloudiness = bacteria)\n- Test on agar plate before committing to grain\n\n### Tips\n- One spore print can make 10-20+ syringes\n- Store spore syringes in fridge (36-46°F) for up to 12 months\n- Always test on agar first — spore syringes have higher contamination risk than LC\n- Some growers add a tiny amount of honey to solution to help germination", equipment_needed: ["SAB or flow hood", "Sterile syringes", "Sterile needles", "Pressure cooker", "Spore print"], safety_warnings: ["Needle safety", "Sterile technique critical", "Never inject spore syringes into your body"], success_rate: 85.0, is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Environmental Controls for Fruiting Rooms", category: "Fruiting", difficulty_level: "Advanced", estimated_time: "Full build: 1-2 days", content: "## Environmental Controls for Fruiting Rooms\n\n### Purpose\nDesign and implement automated environmental controls for consistent mushroom fruiting.\n\n### Key Parameters\n- **Temperature**: Species-dependent (typically 55-75°F)\n- **Humidity**: 85-95% RH\n- **CO2**: Below 800ppm for most species (fresh air exchange)\n- **Light**: 12/12 light cycle, indirect 6500K\n\n### Equipment Needed\n- Humidifier (ultrasonic or cool-mist, commercial grade)\n- Humidity controller (Inkbird IHC-200 or similar)\n- Exhaust fan (inline duct fan, sized for room)\n- Fresh air intake with HEPA filter\n- CO2 monitor (optional but recommended)\n- Timer or smart plug for lighting\n- Hygrometer/thermometer combo\n- Mini-split or space heater with thermostat (for temperature)\n\n### Design Principles\n1. **Humidity first**: This is the most critical parameter. Ultrasonic humidifiers connected to humidity controllers maintain setpoint automatically\n2. **FAE schedule**: Use timer to run exhaust fan for 5-10 minutes every 1-2 hours. This replaces CO2-rich air with fresh air\n3. **Positive pressure**: Optional — slightly pressurize room through HEPA-filtered intake to prevent contamination\n4. **Light cycle**: 12 hours on / 12 hours off. Standard 6500K LED shop lights work perfectly\n5. **Temperature**: Most species fruit in 55-68°F range. Mini-split AC/heater provides best control\n\n### Automation Options\n- **Basic**: Inkbird controllers + timers ($100-200)\n- **Intermediate**: Smart plugs with scheduling ($200-400)\n- **Advanced**: Arduino/Raspberry Pi with sensors + relays ($300-600)\n- **Commercial**: Full PLC control system ($1000+)\n\n### Tips\n- Start simple and add complexity as needed\n- Monitor before automating — understand your room's behavior first\n- Insulated rooms are much easier to control\n- Sealed rooms with controlled intake/exhaust give best results\n- Keep spare humidifiers — they're the component most likely to fail", equipment_needed: ["Humidifier", "Humidity controller", "Exhaust fan", "HEPA filter", "CO2 monitor", "Lighting", "Temperature control"], safety_warnings: ["Electrical safety in wet environment", "GFCI outlets required", "Prevent standing water", "Regular cleaning to prevent biofilm in humidifiers"], success_rate: 90.0, is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Agar-to-Grain Transfer", category: "Spawn Production", difficulty_level: "Intermediate", estimated_time: "30-60 minutes per batch", content: "## Agar-to-Grain Transfer\n\n### Purpose\nTransfer clean mycelium cultures from agar plates to sterilized grain spawn for expansion.\n\n### Materials Needed\n- Colonized agar plate with clean culture\n- Sterilized grain jars (rye, wheat, oats)\n- Scalpel with #10 or #11 blade\n- Alcohol lamp or butane torch\n- 70% isopropyl alcohol\n- Flow hood or SAB\n\n### Procedure\n1. **Setup workspace**: Turn on flow hood 15 min prior, or prepare SAB with 70% ISO wipe and spray\n2. **Stage materials**: Place agar plate and grain jar in workspace\n3. **Flame scalpel**: Heat blade until red-hot, let cool 10 seconds\n4. **Cut wedges**: Open agar plate, cut 3-4 small wedges (~1cm square) from leading edge of mycelium growth\n5. **Open grain jar**: Crack lid of grain jar just enough to insert wedge\n6. **Transfer**: Slide agar wedge into grain jar. Place wedge on top of grain surface\n7. **Seal immediately**: Close grain jar lid\n8. **Repeat**: Cut additional wedges for more jars. Re-flame scalpel between plates\n9. **Shake gently**: Give jar a light swirl to distribute wedge\n10. **Incubate**: Store at 75-78°F in dark location\n\n### Post-Transfer Care\n- Check jars daily for first 5 days for contamination signs\n- Mycelium should be visible growing from wedge in 3-7 days\n- Shake jar at 20-30% colonization to speed things up\n- Full colonization typically takes 2-4 weeks\n\n### Tips\n- Always transfer from the leading edge — this is the cleanest, most vigorous growth\n- Multiple wedges per jar = faster colonization\n- Don't over-shake — it can stress young mycelium\n- If you see tomentose (fluffy) growth, your genetics may benefit from more transfers to isolate rhizomorphic (ropy) growth", equipment_needed: ["Flow hood or SAB", "Scalpel", "Alcohol lamp", "70% isopropyl alcohol"], safety_warnings: ["Scalpel is extremely sharp", "Flame safety", "Sterile technique critical to prevent contamination"], success_rate: 90.0, is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
]

