const knowledgeBase = [
  { title: "Understanding Substrate Types for Mushroom Cultivation", slug: "substrate-types-guide", category: "Substrates", content: "Substrate is the material that mushroom mycelium feeds on to grow. Choosing the right substrate is one of the most important decisions in mushroom cultivation.\n\n## Common Substrate Types\n\n### Straw\nWheat straw is the classic substrate for oyster mushrooms. It's cheap, widely available, and easy to prepare via pasteurization. Chop to 2-3 inch lengths for best results.\n\n### Hardwood Sawdust\nOak, maple, beech, and other hardwoods provide excellent nutrition for wood-loving species. Often supplemented with bran or soy hulls. Must be sterilized (not just pasteurized) when supplemented.\n\n### Masters Mix\n50/50 hardwood sawdust and soy hull pellets by dry weight. The industry standard for commercial growers. Works for Lion's Mane, King Oyster, Pioppino, Chestnut, and many others.\n\n### Coffee Grounds\nFree and pre-pasteurized (from brewing). Best mixed 50/50 with another substrate. Use within 24 hours of brewing. High nitrogen content but prone to contamination.\n\n### Hardwood Logs\nOak, maple, and beech logs are used for shiitake, oyster, and lion's mane outdoor cultivation. Low-tech, long-producing (3-7 years per log).\n\n### Manure-Based\nHorse or cow manure composted with straw. The traditional substrate for Agaricus (button/portobello) and Psilocybe species. Requires proper composting.\n\n## Moisture Content\nTarget 60-65% moisture for most supplemented substrates. Use the 'squeeze test' — a firm squeeze should produce only a few drops of water.", summary: "Complete guide to mushroom cultivation substrates including straw, hardwood, masters mix, coffee grounds, and logs.", tags: ["substrate", "beginner", "growing", "materials"], difficulty_level: "beginner", is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Sterile Technique Fundamentals", slug: "sterile-technique-fundamentals", category: "Lab Skills", content: "Sterile technique is the foundation of successful mushroom cultivation. Without it, contamination will destroy your cultures before mushrooms can fruit.\n\n## Why Sterile Technique Matters\nMushroom mycelium grows slowly compared to mold and bacteria. A single contamination event introduces millions of competitor organisms that will outcompete your culture.\n\n## The Clean Environment Hierarchy\n1. **Laminar Flow Hood** (best) — HEPA-filtered air creates a clean workspace\n2. **Still Air Box (SAB)** — settled air with no currents prevents airborne contamination\n3. **Clean Room** — a dedicated, sanitized room without a hood\n4. **Open Air** — worst option, highest contamination risk\n\n## Core Principles\n- **Flame sterilize** all tools between transfers\n- **Spray everything** with 70% isopropyl alcohol\n- **Work quickly** but deliberately — every second open containers are exposed is a risk\n- **Upstream workflow** — in front of flow hood, work behind open containers\n- **Never reach over** open plates or jars\n- **Minimize air movement** — no fans, closed doors, slow movements\n\n## Common Mistakes\n- Using 90-99% ISO instead of 70% (70% is more effective at killing microbes)\n- Not flame-sterilizing between transfers\n- Working too far from flow hood face\n- Talking, coughing, or breathing over open cultures\n- Wearing loose clothing that creates air currents", summary: "Essential sterile technique for mushroom cultivation including clean environment setup and core contamination prevention principles.", tags: ["sterile technique", "beginner", "contamination prevention", "lab skills"], difficulty_level: "beginner", is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Mushroom Life Cycle Explained", slug: "mushroom-life-cycle", category: "Biology", content: "Understanding the mushroom life cycle helps growers optimize each stage for better yields.\n\n## The Complete Life Cycle\n\n### 1. Spore Germination\nSpores land on a suitable substrate and germinate, producing thin threads called hyphae. Each spore produces monokaryotic (single-nucleus) mycelium.\n\n### 2. Mating and Dikaryotic Mycelium\nTwo compatible monokaryotic mycelia fuse to create dikaryotic mycelium (two nuclei per cell). This is the fertile mycelium capable of producing mushrooms.\n\n### 3. Colonization\nDikaryotic mycelium aggressively colonizes the substrate, breaking down and consuming nutrients. This is the 'spawn run' phase growers are familiar with.\n\n### 4. Primordia Formation (Pinning)\nWhen conditions change (temperature drop, increased fresh air, light exposure), the mycelium forms tiny pin-like structures called primordia. These are baby mushrooms.\n\n### 5. Fruiting Body Development\nPrimordia develop into mature mushrooms (fruiting bodies). The mushroom's job is to produce and release spores for reproduction.\n\n### 6. Spore Release\nMature mushrooms release millions of spores from their gills, pores, or teeth. Spores are carried by air currents to new locations.\n\n## What Growers Control\n- **Colonization**: Temperature, darkness, time\n- **Pinning triggers**: Temperature drop, fresh air exchange, light\n- **Fruit development**: Humidity, temperature, air exchange, light cycle", summary: "Complete breakdown of the mushroom life cycle from spore germination through fruiting and spore release.", tags: ["biology", "life cycle", "beginner", "education"], difficulty_level: "beginner", is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Humidity and Fresh Air Exchange Balance", slug: "humidity-fae-balance", category: "Environmental Control", content: "The balance between humidity and fresh air exchange (FAE) is the most challenging aspect of mushroom fruiting for new growers.\n\n## The Core Tension\n- Mushrooms need **high humidity** (85-95%) to develop properly\n- Mushrooms need **fresh air** (low CO2) to form normal caps and stems\n- Fresh air **lowers humidity** — this is the fundamental challenge\n\n## Signs of Insufficient FAE (Too Much CO2)\n- Elongated stems with tiny caps\n- 'Leggy' or reaching mushrooms\n- Fuzzy feet (aerial mycelium at base of stems)\n- Mushrooms growing toward air gaps\n\n## Signs of Insufficient Humidity\n- Cracked or split caps\n- Dried-out pins that abort\n- Curled or crispy edges\n- Poor yields despite healthy colonization\n\n## Solutions\n\n### For Small Scale (Monotub)\n- Polyfill in holes provides passive air exchange\n- Mist walls 2-3 times daily\n- Fan with lid for 30 seconds when misting\n- Perlite humidity layer at bottom (4 inches, soaked)\n\n### For Fruiting Rooms\n- Humidifier connected to humidity controller (Inkbird IHC-200)\n- Exhaust fan on timer (5-10 min every 1-2 hours)\n- Fresh air intake with filter\n- Sealed room for maximum control\n\n## The Golden Rule\nIf you see fuzzy feet, increase FAE. If you see cracking caps, increase humidity. Adjust one variable at a time.", summary: "How to balance humidity and fresh air exchange for optimal mushroom fruiting.", tags: ["humidity", "FAE", "environmental control", "troubleshooting"], difficulty_level: "intermediate", is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Introduction to Medicinal Mushrooms", slug: "medicinal-mushrooms-intro", category: "Medicinal", content: "Medicinal mushrooms have been used in traditional medicine for thousands of years. Modern research is validating many of these traditional uses.\n\n## The Big 5 Medicinal Mushrooms\n\n### Lion's Mane (Hericium erinaceus)\n**Key compounds**: Hericenones, erinacines\n**Research focus**: Nerve Growth Factor stimulation, cognitive support, neuroprotection\n**Traditional use**: Brain health, digestive support\n**How to use**: Fresh (culinary), dried powder, dual extract tincture\n\n### Reishi (Ganoderma lucidum)\n**Key compounds**: Triterpenoids, beta-glucans, polysaccharides\n**Research focus**: Immune modulation, stress adaptation, sleep support\n**Traditional use**: 'Mushroom of Immortality' in TCM, longevity tonic\n**How to use**: Tea, dual extract tincture, powdered extract\n\n### Turkey Tail (Trametes versicolor)\n**Key compounds**: PSK (Polysaccharide-K), PSP\n**Research focus**: Immune support, gut microbiome, adjunct cancer therapy\n**Traditional use**: Immune tonic in TCM and Japanese medicine\n**How to use**: Tea, powdered extract, hot water extract\n\n### Cordyceps (Cordyceps militaris)\n**Key compounds**: Cordycepin, adenosine\n**Research focus**: Energy, athletic performance, respiratory health\n**Traditional use**: Energy and vitality tonic in TCM\n**How to use**: Powdered extract, tincture, capsules\n\n### Chaga (Inonotus obliquus)\n**Key compounds**: Betulinic acid, melanin, polysaccharides\n**Research focus**: Antioxidant, anti-inflammatory, immune support\n**Traditional use**: Northern European and Russian folk medicine\n**How to use**: Tea (decoction), dual extract tincture\n\n## Extraction Methods\n- **Hot water**: Extracts polysaccharides and beta-glucans\n- **Alcohol (ethanol)**: Extracts triterpenoids and other non-water-soluble compounds\n- **Dual extraction**: Both methods combined for full spectrum of compounds", summary: "Overview of the top 5 medicinal mushrooms, their key compounds, research focus, and preparation methods.", tags: ["medicinal", "lion's mane", "reishi", "turkey tail", "cordyceps", "chaga", "health"], difficulty_level: "beginner", is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Mushroom Growing in the Southwest US", slug: "southwest-growing-guide", category: "Regional Growing", content: "Growing mushrooms in the American Southwest (Arizona, New Mexico, Nevada, West Texas) presents unique challenges and opportunities.\n\n## Challenges\n\n### Low Humidity\nThe Southwest averages 10-30% ambient humidity. Mushrooms need 85-95%. This means fruiting chambers MUST be sealed and humidity-controlled.\n\n### High Temperatures\nSummer temperatures exceeding 110°F make it impossible to fruit most species without cooling. Indoor climate control is essential.\n\n### Water Scarcity\nWater is precious in the desert. Recirculating humidification systems and water-efficient substrate preparation methods are important.\n\n## Opportunities\n\n### Year-Round Indoor Growing\nWith climate control, the Southwest's stable indoor temperatures make year-round production very feasible.\n\n### Tropical Species\nWarm-loving species like Pink Oyster and Golden Oyster thrive in Southwest ambient temperatures during shoulder seasons (March-May, September-November).\n\n### Low Pest Pressure\nDry climates have fewer fungus gnats and mites compared to humid regions.\n\n### Market Demand\nFewer local mushroom farms means less competition. Fresh gourmet mushrooms command premium prices at farmers markets and restaurants.\n\n## Southwest-Optimized Setup\n1. **Sealed fruiting room** with mini-split for cooling\n2. **Commercial humidifier** (ultrasonic) with humidity controller\n3. **HEPA-filtered fresh air intake** (desert dust is real)\n4. **Evaporative cooling** assist where possible\n5. **Insulated growing space** to reduce cooling costs\n\n## Best Species for Southwest Growers\n- Pink Oyster (warm temps)\n- Golden Oyster (warm temps)\n- Blue Oyster (cooler months or climate-controlled)\n- Lion's Mane (climate-controlled)\n- King Oyster (climate-controlled)", summary: "Guide to growing mushrooms in the desert Southwest with solutions for low humidity, high temperatures, and water conservation.", tags: ["southwest", "desert growing", "regional", "climate control", "Arizona", "New Mexico"], difficulty_level: "intermediate", is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Grain Spawn Types Compared", slug: "grain-spawn-comparison", category: "Spawn Production", content: "Not all grain spawn is created equal. Each grain type has pros and cons that affect colonization speed, contamination resistance, and mushroom yield.\n\n## Rye Berries (Industry Standard)\n**Pros**: Excellent nutrition, small grain size (more inoculation points), widely available\n**Cons**: Slightly tricky hydration (easy to over-soak), can be expensive\n**Best for**: All species, commercial production\n\n## Whole Oats\n**Pros**: Very cheap, widely available at feed stores, forgiving moisture tolerance\n**Cons**: Larger grain = fewer inoculation points, slightly lower nutrition than rye\n**Best for**: Budget-conscious growers, beginners\n\n## Wheat Berries\n**Pros**: Good nutrition, small grain size, readily available\n**Cons**: Prone to bursting if over-soaked, sticky when too wet\n**Best for**: All species, similar to rye as a premium option\n\n## Wild Bird Seed (WBS)\n**Pros**: Very cheap ($15/50lbs at feed stores), millet-based = tiny grains = massive inoculation points\n**Cons**: Inconsistent mixes, may contain sunflower seeds (can go rancid), harder to hydrate evenly\n**Best for**: Budget growing, fast colonization\n\n## Brown Rice\n**Pros**: Available everywhere, very nutritious, fine grain\n**Cons**: Expensive for bulk, sticky, prone to bacterial contamination\n**Best for**: Small batches, BRF jars (PF Tek)\n\n## Popcorn\n**Pros**: Cheap, easy to hydrate, large kernels easy to break apart\n**Cons**: Large grain = fewer inoculation points, can be starchy\n**Best for**: Beginners, large species like King Oyster\n\n## Hydration Tips (Universal)\n- Soak 12-24 hours, simmer 15-20 minutes\n- Drain completely, dry surface moisture\n- Add 1 tbsp gypsum per quart to prevent clumping\n- Grains should feel dry to touch before loading jars", summary: "Comparison of grain spawn types including rye berries, oats, wheat, wild bird seed, brown rice, and popcorn.", tags: ["spawn", "grain", "comparison", "beginner", "materials"], difficulty_level: "beginner", is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Troubleshooting Slow Colonization", slug: "troubleshooting-slow-colonization", category: "Troubleshooting", content: "When your grain spawn or substrate isn't colonizing at expected rates, systematic troubleshooting helps identify the cause.\n\n## Expected Colonization Timelines\n- **Grain spawn**: 2-4 weeks for full colonization\n- **Bulk substrate**: 7-14 days for surface colonization\n- **Agar plates**: 7-14 days for full plate colonization\n\n## Common Causes of Slow Colonization\n\n### 1. Temperature Too Low\nMycelium grows fastest at 75-80°F for most species. Below 65°F, growth slows dramatically. Below 55°F, most species go dormant.\n**Fix**: Move to warmer location, use heat mat (with thermostat), or incubation chamber.\n\n### 2. Weak or Old Culture\nCultures lose vigor over many transfers. Spore syringes germinate slower than LC or agar transfers.\n**Fix**: Use liquid culture or fresh agar transfer instead of spore syringe. Limit to 5-7 transfers from original isolation.\n\n### 3. Too Much Moisture\nExcess water creates anaerobic conditions that slow mycelium growth and invite bacteria.\n**Fix**: Ensure grains pass the 'newspaper test' — grains placed on newspaper should not leave wet marks.\n\n### 4. Insufficient Gas Exchange\nMycelium needs oxygen. Sealed containers without gas exchange ports will stall.\n**Fix**: Ensure jar lids have micropore tape or filter patches. Don't seal grow bags completely.\n\n### 5. Competing Organisms\nSubclinical contamination can slow growth before visible signs appear. Bacteria especially can inhibit mycelium.\n**Fix**: Inspect carefully for off-colors or smells. Check agar isolation plates.\n\n### 6. Incorrect Substrate pH\nMost mushroom species prefer slightly acidic pH (5.5-6.5). Overly alkaline or acidic substrate inhibits growth.\n**Fix**: Add gypsum to buffer pH. Use proper substrate recipes.\n\n### 7. Compacted Substrate\nTightly packed grain or substrate lacks oxygen and slows colonization.\n**Fix**: Don't over-pack jars. Leave headspace. Shake grain jars at 30% colonization.", summary: "Systematic guide to diagnosing and fixing slow mushroom colonization in grain spawn and bulk substrate.", tags: ["troubleshooting", "colonization", "slow growth", "problems", "beginner"], difficulty_level: "beginner", is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Commercial Mushroom Farming Business Basics", slug: "commercial-farming-basics", category: "Business", content: "Transitioning from hobby to commercial mushroom farming requires understanding the business fundamentals.\n\n## Revenue Models\n\n### Direct to Consumer\n- Farmers markets: $12-20/lb for gourmet mushrooms\n- CSA (Community Supported Agriculture) shares\n- Online sales (dried, extracts)\n- Farm stand or u-pick events\n\n### Wholesale\n- Restaurants: $8-14/lb (build relationships with chefs)\n- Grocery stores: $6-10/lb (consistent volume required)\n- Distributors: $4-8/lb (lowest margin, highest volume)\n\n### Value-Added Products\n- Dried mushrooms: $30-60/lb\n- Mushroom powders: $20-40/lb\n- Tinctures and extracts: $25-60 per bottle\n- Growing kits: $20-35 each\n- Spawn sales: $15-30 per bag\n\n## Startup Costs (Small Scale, 100-200 lbs/week)\n- Grow room build-out: $5,000-15,000\n- Lab equipment (flow hood, PC, supplies): $3,000-8,000\n- Substrate production area: $2,000-5,000\n- Initial supplies and spawn: $1,000-3,000\n- Packaging and branding: $500-2,000\n- **Total**: $11,500-33,000\n\n## Key Metrics\n- **Biological efficiency (BE)**: lbs fresh mushrooms / lbs dry substrate × 100. Target: 75-150% depending on species\n- **Contamination rate**: Track by batch. Industry standard < 5%. Above 10% = process problem\n- **Yield per sq ft**: Important for space planning. Oysters: 1-2 lbs/sq ft per flush\n- **Labor hours per lb**: Track to ensure profitability\n\n## Legal Requirements\n- Business license and permits\n- Cottage food laws (vary by state)\n- Food safety certification (often required for wholesale)\n- Liability insurance\n- Zoning compliance for commercial growing", summary: "Overview of starting a commercial mushroom farming business including revenue models, startup costs, and key metrics.", tags: ["commercial", "business", "farming", "market", "revenue"], difficulty_level: "intermediate", is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Understanding Biological Efficiency", slug: "biological-efficiency", category: "Advanced Growing", content: "Biological efficiency (BE) is the most important metric for measuring mushroom cultivation success.\n\n## The Formula\n**BE = (Fresh mushroom weight / Dry substrate weight) × 100**\n\nExample: 2 lbs fresh mushrooms from 2 lbs dry substrate = 100% BE\n\n## Why It Matters\nBE tells you how efficiently your process converts substrate into mushrooms. Higher BE = better genetics, better process, more profit.\n\n## Typical BE by Species\n- **Oyster mushrooms**: 100-200% (very efficient)\n- **Shiitake (supplemented sawdust)**: 75-125%\n- **Lion's Mane**: 60-100%\n- **King Oyster**: 60-90%\n- **Maitake**: 40-70%\n- **Reishi (antlers)**: 30-50%\n\n## Factors That Affect BE\n\n### Genetics\nSome strains simply produce more than others. Commercial strains are selected for high BE over years of isolation.\n\n### Substrate Nutrition\nProper C:N ratio (carbon to nitrogen) is critical. Most species want 30-60:1. Over-supplementation increases contamination risk without proportional yield gains.\n\n### Environmental Conditions\nOptimal temperature, humidity, and FAE during fruiting maximize BE. Even small deviations reduce yields.\n\n### Flush Management\nMost of your yield comes from flush 1 (60-70%) and flush 2 (20-30%). Flush 3+ provides diminishing returns.\n\n### Spawn Rate\nHigher spawn rates (15-20%) colonize faster and generally produce better first flushes. Lower rates (5-10%) save spawn but risk contamination and lower BE.\n\n## Tracking BE\nTrack BE for every batch. Create a spreadsheet with: date, species, strain, substrate recipe, spawn rate, environmental conditions, and yield per flush. Over time, patterns emerge that optimize your process.", summary: "Deep dive into biological efficiency — the key metric for measuring mushroom cultivation productivity.", tags: ["biological efficiency", "yield", "metrics", "advanced", "commercial"], difficulty_level: "advanced", is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Agar Culture Isolation and Cleanup", slug: "agar-culture-isolation", category: "Lab Skills", content: "Agar work is how you isolate clean, vigorous mushroom genetics from wild specimens, spore prints, or contaminated cultures.\n\n## Why Isolate on Agar?\n- Clean up contaminated cultures\n- Isolate monocultures from multi-spore germination\n- Select for desirable traits (fast growth, rhizomorphic morphology)\n- Create long-term culture storage\n\n## Types of Agar Media\n- **MEA (Malt Extract Agar)**: General purpose, works for all species\n- **PDA (Potato Dextrose Agar)**: Good nutrition, some species prefer it\n- **Dog Food Agar (DFA)**: Cheap and effective — yes, really\n- **Water Agar**: Low nutrition, used specifically for cleanup transfers\n\n## The Isolation Process\n\n### Step 1: Initial Transfer\nTake a tissue sample from inside a fresh mushroom (tear open, take from center where it's sterile) and place on agar plate.\n\n### Step 2: Wait and Observe (5-7 days)\nMycelium will grow outward from tissue. Contaminants may also appear. This is normal for wild specimens.\n\n### Step 3: Transfer Leading Edge\nUsing sterile scalpel, cut a small wedge from the leading edge of clean mycelium growth — as far from any contamination as possible. Transfer to fresh plate.\n\n### Step 4: Repeat Until Clean\nMay take 2-5 transfers to get fully clean culture. Each transfer moves you further from contamination.\n\n### Step 5: Isolate for Traits\nOnce clean, look for sectors of different growth morphology. Transfer rhizomorphic (ropy, strand-like) growth preferentially — this typically produces better fruiters.\n\n## Pro Tips\n- Water agar for first transfer (low nutrition slows contaminants more than mycelium)\n- Rich media (MEA) for subsequent transfers once culture is cleaner\n- Always cut from leading edge, never from center\n- Store clean cultures at 36-40°F in sealed parafilm — viable for months to years\n- Label EVERYTHING: species, strain, transfer number, date, source", summary: "Complete guide to isolating and cleaning mushroom cultures using agar plate techniques.", tags: ["agar", "culture", "isolation", "lab skills", "genetics"], difficulty_level: "intermediate", is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
  { title: "Common Mushroom Growing Mistakes", slug: "common-growing-mistakes", category: "Troubleshooting", content: "Every mushroom grower makes mistakes. Here are the most common ones and how to avoid them.\n\n## Beginner Mistakes\n\n### 1. Skipping Sterile Technique\n'It'll be fine' is the motto of failed grows. Even for simple projects like straw bucket oysters, basic cleanliness matters.\n\n### 2. Over-Misting\nNew growers spray water directly on substrate and mushrooms. This causes bacterial blotch and waterlogged pins. Mist the walls and air, not the mushrooms.\n\n### 3. Not Enough Fresh Air\nCO2 buildup is invisible. If your mushrooms have long stems and tiny caps, they're screaming for air.\n\n### 4. Impatience\nOpening containers to 'check on things' introduces contaminants. Leave colonizing substrate alone.\n\n### 5. Wrong Substrate for Species\nNot all substrates work for all species. Lion's Mane on straw = failure. Oysters on un-supplemented sawdust = poor yields.\n\n## Intermediate Mistakes\n\n### 6. Over-Supplementation\nAdding too much nutrition (bran, soy hulls) to substrate dramatically increases contamination risk. Stick to proven recipes.\n\n### 7. Ignoring Temperature\nRunning incubation too hot (above 82°F) invites thermophilic contaminants. Fruiting too warm stunts many species.\n\n### 8. Not Tracking Data\nWithout records, you can't improve. Log every batch: substrate recipe, spawn rate, temperatures, colonization time, yield.\n\n### 9. Too Many Species at Once\nFocus on 2-3 species and master them before expanding. Each species has nuances.\n\n### 10. Reusing Contaminated Materials\n'It was only a little trich' — contamination spores persist. Never reuse contaminated substrate or containers without thorough sterilization.", summary: "The top 10 mushroom growing mistakes beginners and intermediates make and how to avoid them.", tags: ["mistakes", "troubleshooting", "beginner", "tips"], difficulty_level: "beginner", is_premium: false, view_count: 0 },
]

